                    <td align="left" valign="top"><p class="bodytext"><em>Police Foundation &amp; NYPD</em> launch college loan reimbursements. A donor provides $1.5 million to kick it off. <br />[October 22, 2007] </p>
                      <p class="bodytext">New York City Police Foundation Chair Valerie Salembier and Police Commissioner Raymond W. Kelly announced a program to assist new police officers in reducing significant portions of their outstanding college loans.</p>
                      <p class="bodytext">The creation of the college loan reimbursement program is designed to enhance the NYPD&rsquo;s ability to recruit and retain qualified candidates. At a joint press conference at Police Headquarters, Ms. Salembier and Commissioner Kelly announced that long-time Police Foundation benefactor, Richard Fields, had provided a gift of $1.5 million to launch the program.</p>
                      <p class="bodytext">The NYPD class that begins in January 2008 will be eligible for up to $15,000 each over five years to reduce or eliminate their college loan burdens. A survey of recent recruit classes disclosed that recruits carried an average college loan debt of $16,000.</p>
                      <p class="bodytext">&ldquo;We have been seeking ways to augment our recruitment efforts and to financially assist new recruits upon graduation from the Police Academy. We&rsquo;re confident that this new reimbursement program does both,&rdquo; Commissioner Kelly said. &ldquo;There&rsquo;s no more pressing issue facing the Department today than attracting qualified candidates to the Police Academy. The generosity of Richard Fields has been inspirational.&rdquo;</p>
                      <p class="bodytext">&ldquo;This is an important inducement for women and men to come forward and join the ranks of the New York City Police Department at a moment of tremendous opportunity-and need,&rdquo; said Ms. Salembier.</p>
                      <p class="bodytext">Ms. Salembier is also publisher of Harper&rsquo;s Bazaar.</p>
                      <p class="bodytext">&ldquo;We&rsquo;ve been able to make these funds available through the visionary contributions of civic-minded citizens. Richard Fields of Coastal Development, LLC, has set an extraordinary example through his donation of $1.5 million to kick off the program. We need many more New Yorkers, along with additional leaders from the business community, to come forward and help us insure that the NYPD continues to recruit the best and the brightest,&rdquo; Ms. Salembier said. </p>
                      <p class="bodytext">&ldquo;As a native of the Bronx, New York City and the NYPD, in particular, have been close to my heart. I am just fortunate enough now to help in a tangible way with my support for this program,&rdquo; said Mr. Fields.</p>
                      <p class="bodytext">The NYC Police Foundation will be responsible for managing and administering the initiative. Awards of the college loan reimbursement program will be paid out in five annual installments to the lending institutions of candidates who have outstanding loans, with the first payment to be made upon graduation from the Police Academy. Awards will be made over a five year period. To be eligible for reimbursement, candidates will be required to remain employed during that period. The first awards will be distributed in June when the January 2008 class graduates from the Police Academy. The process of promoting the program and identifying qualified candidates will begin immediately.</p>
                      <p class="bodytext">The NYC Police Foundation encourages additional donations. More information about the college loan program can be received by calling the foundation at <strong>212-751-8170</strong>.  Checks should be made out to the NYC Police Foundation and mailed to the foundation headquarters at <strong>345 Park Avenue, New York, NY 10154</strong>. <br />
